[
    {
        "id": "oauth2-auth-flow",
        "type": "tab",
        "label": "OAuth2 Authenticated API Example",
        "disabled": false,
        "info": "## OAuth2 Authenticated API Example\n\nThis flow demonstrates OAuth2/OpenID Connect authentication using Keycloak.\n\n### Prerequisites\n\n1. **Keycloak Server**: You need a running Keycloak instance\n2. **Realm**: Create a realm (e.g., 'my-realm')\n3. **Client**: Create a confidential client with:\n   - Client ID: my-api-client\n   - Client Protocol: openid-connect\n   - Access Type: confidential\n   - Service Accounts Enabled: Yes (if using client credentials)\n4. **Roles**: Create realm roles:\n   - `user` - Basic access\n   - `admin` - Administrative access\n5. **User**: Create a test user with the 'user' role\n\n### Endpoints\n\n| Method | Path | Auth Required | Scopes |\n|--------|------|---------------|--------|\n| GET | /api/v1/public/health | No | - |\n| GET | /api/v1/user/profile | Yes | user |\n| GET | /api/v1/admin/users | Yes | admin |\n| POST | /api/v1/admin/users | Yes | admin AND user:write |\n\n### Testing with cURL\n\n```bash\n# Get access token from Keycloak\nTOKEN=$(curl -s -X POST \\\n  'http://localhost:8080/realms/my-realm/protocol/openid-connect/token' \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded' \\\n  -d 'client_id=my-api-client' \\\n  -d 'client_secret=your-client-secret' \\\n  -d 'grant_type=password' \\\n  -d 'username=testuser' \\\n  -d 'password=testpassword' \\\n  | jq -r '.access_token')\n\n# Public endpoint (no auth required)\ncurl http://localhost:3001/api/v1/public/health\n\n# Protected endpoint (requires 'user' role)\ncurl -H \"Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN\" \\\n  http://localhost:3001/api/v1/user/profile\n\n# Admin endpoint (requires 'admin' role)\ncurl -H \"Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN\" \\\n  http://localhost:3001/api/v1/admin/users\n```\n\n### Token Validation\n\nThe api-server validates JWT tokens by:\n1. Fetching JWKS (JSON Web Key Set) from Keycloak\n2. Verifying token signature\n3. Checking token expiration and issuer\n4. Extracting roles/scopes from token claims\n5. Comparing against endpoint's required scopes"
    },
